          "body": "Ezra 8:31-36 resolves every thread the chapter opened. The 'hand of our God' that Ezra had publicly declared (8:22) is confirmed in identical language over the road (8:31): 'He delivered us from the hand of the enemy and the ambushes by the way.' The refused military escort was not a gamble — it was faith vindicated. The three days of rest on arrival (8:32) give way to the formal accounting of the treasure (8:33-34), and then to the community's first act in Jerusalem: burnt offerings for all Israel — twelve bulls, ninety-six rams, seventy-seven lambs, twelve sin-offering goats (8:35). The numbers are deliberately whole-Israel theology. The actual company was a fraction of the nation; the offering claimed the full covenantal identity. Finally, the king's edicts are delivered to the provincial officials, who 'supported the people and the house of God' (8:36). The chapter that began with personal faith (Ezra's refusal of troops) ends with imperial infrastructure serving the worship of Israel's God — the widest possible confirmation of the bilateral principle in verse 22: His hand is favorably disposed to all who seek Him."
